White spot syndrome virus (Inf. with), Australia
----------------------------------------------------------------
Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Started: 18 Aug 2022
Confirmed: 23 Aug 2022
Reported: 24 Aug 2022
Reason for notification: 1st occurrence in a zone or a compartment
Causal agent: White spot syndrome virus
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, laboratory
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country.

Outbreak location: Yamba, Clarence Valley, New South Wales
Started: 18 Aug 2022
Epidemiological unit: farm
Animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered or killed for commercial use / Vaccinated
Giant tiger prawn or black tiger shrimp (_Penaeus monodon_): Penaeidae-Farmed crustaceans / 400 / - / - / 400 / - / -

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive
Epidemiological comments: routine testing of prawn brood stock (_Penaeus monodon_) held in a biosecure facility was positive for white spot syndrome virus (WSSV) and subsequent testing confirmed WSSV. All animals within the facility have been destroyed and the facility is in the process of being decontaminated. The outbreak is contained to a single affected biosecure facility. Investigations into the source of the outbreak are ongoing.

Control measures at event level
Domestic control measures applied: traceability; stamping out; quarantine; official disposal of carcasses, by-products, and waste; movement control; disinfection

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Australian Centre for Disease Preparedness National Laboratory / ciant tiger prawn or black tiger shrimp / polymerase chain reaction (PCR) / 23 Aug 2022 / positive
Australian Centre for Disease Preparedness National Laboratory / giant tiger prawn or black tiger shrimp / real-time polymerase chain reaction (real-time PCR) / 23 Aug 2022 / positive
Australian Centre for Disease Preparedness National Laboratory / giant tiger prawn or black tiger shrimp / real-time polymerase chain reaction (real-time PCR) / 23 Aug 2022 / positive
Elizabeth Macarthur Agriculture Institute (EMAI), Virology Laboratory / giant tiger prawn or black tiger shrimp / real-time polymerase chain reaction (real-time PCR) / 20 Aug 2022 / positive

