Communicated by:
ProMED

[White spot disease is a highly contagious viral disease of decapod crustaceans including prawns, crabs, yabbies, and lobsters. The disease is caused by white spot syndrome virus.

An identification Field Guide of White spot disease is available at https://www.agriculture.gov.au/sites/default/files/documents/infection-white-spot-syndrome-virus.pdf

History of the disease in Australia:

"White spot disease was first detected in South East Queensland in December 2016. Seven prawn farms on the Logan River were affected from late 2016 to early 2017. The virus was also first detected in wild populations of crustaceans, such as prawns and crabs in the northern part of Moreton Bay in early 2017.

Prawns on the infected farms were destroyed to eradicate the disease and farms later returned to production. Prawn farmers on the Logan River have applied a range of enhanced biosecurity measures to reduce the risk of a disease recurrence.

A Movement Regulated Area (MRA) in South East Queensland, which includes the Logan River area and Moreton Bay, was established in early 2017 to prevent movement of crustaceans and worms from the area, unless they are cooked or treated in a way that will de-activate the virus.

White spot syndrome virus has established in some populations of wild crustaceans within the MRA. A national surveillance program that commenced in 2017 demonstrated that all areas of Australia, outside of the MRA, have remained free from the virus.

Movement and fishing restrictions remain in place in the Queensland MRA".
(Source: National pest & disease outbreaks, Australia https://www.outbreak.gov.au/current-responses-to-outbreaks/white-spot-disease)
- Mod.CRD

